## Project Conclusion

### Best performing model: SVM RBF (F1=0.7359)
The RBF kernel's ability to draw non-linear boundaries in 
implicit infinite-dimensional space made it best suited for 
separating the 8 emotion clusters in our 112-feature space.

### Why deep ANN (0.724) nearly matches SVM
Both model non-linear boundaries. SVM does it analytically 
via the kernel trick. ANN does it by learning intermediate 
representations. With only 1956 training samples and 112 
features, SVM's analytical solution has an advantage over 
gradient-based ANN training.

### Hardest emotions across all models
Sad (F1≈0.48) and fearful (F1≈0.50) were consistently the 
hardest. Both are low-to-medium arousal negative emotions 
with overlapping spectral profiles. Even humans confuse these.

### What limited performance
1. 112 hand-crafted features miss temporal dynamics
2. Only 1956 training samples — small for deep learning
3. Actor-dependent patterns — model may learn voice identity
4. Emotions exist on a continuum, not discrete categories

### What would push beyond 75%
1. Pre-trained embeddings (wav2vec2, HuBERT) — learn features 
   directly from raw audio on massive datasets
2. 1D-CNN or LSTM on raw waveform — captures temporal patterns
3. Speaker-independent evaluation — train/test split by actor
4. Data augmentation — pitch shift, time stretch, noise addition